EP  - 180
DO  - 10.1201/9781003537243-10
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85218046479&doi=10.1201%2f9781003537243-10&partnerID=40&md5=f0178ed3a58aa824930c4b630432a207
AB  - Businesses are using post-quantum cryptography (PQC) technologies to safeguard digital data from the increasing computational capabilities of quantum machines. The rise of quantum-safe hybrid ecosystems is a notable shift in cryptographic methodology, merging the security benefits of quantum-resistant algorithms with conventional cryptographic approaches. Quantum computers will possess exceptional ability in handling complex simulations and optimization tasks by the year 2030. Industries such as finance, cybersecurity, pharmaceuticals, and logistics are incorporating quantum computing into their operations. They are utilizing quantum algorithms to do complex risk assessments and facilitate data transmission. The integration of artificial intelligence (AI) and PQC is anticipated to significantly enhance the security and effectiveness of cryptographic systems. Adopting PQC into space communications is essential for ensuring global security and compatibility. Establishing common standards is vital to protect against potential threats and maintain worldwide security. Global collaboration is essential to create policies and ethical principles for PQC adoption and utilization. The ability of quantum computers to decipher encrypted communications raises privacy concerns. By 2030, quantum technologies are expected to make a deep impact on society and culture, leading to the development of a new cultural awareness and preparing humanity for the upcoming quantum revolution. © 2025 selection and editorial matter, Mohammad Hammoudeh, Clinton Firth, Harbaksh Singh, Christoph Capellaro, and Mohamed Al Kuwaiti; individual chapters, the contributors.
