SP  - 31
EP  - 64
DO  - 10.1201/9781003429654-3
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85206282225&doi=10.1201%2f9781003429654-3&partnerID=40&md5=1852155e7fef1db10605048337c01fd6
AB  - Quantum machines, grounded in the principles of quantum mechanics, harness the extraordinary computational power derived from quantum bits (qubits), contrasting with classical machines reliant on classical bits. Qubits, distinguished by properties like superposition and entanglement, empower quantum algorithms to solve intricate problems with exponential speedup. Quantum states, fundamental to quantum mechanics, serve as descriptors for quantum systems, laying the foundation for subsequent calculations. Quantum gates, unitary operators manipulating qubits, are pivotal in quantum computing, extending beyond single-particle systems to encompass multi-particle scenarios. This flexibility finds applications in quantum simulation, optimization, cryptography, machine learning, and more. Quantum computing's potential to revolutionize fields arises from its ability to tackle computationally intractable problems. Applications span quantum simulation, optimization, cryptography, machine learning, chemistry, materials science, financial modeling, and transportation. quantum protocols, including communication and cryptography, leverage unique quantum properties. Prominent quantum algorithms, such as Deutsch-Jozsa, Bernstein-Vazirani, Grover's, and Shor's, exploit qubit features for efficient problem-solving. These algorithms harness superposition and entanglement, allowing parallel calculations across multiple possibilities. In the landscape of quantum computing, the interplay of quantum bits, gates, states, and algorithms showcases the potential for transformative advances in computation. © 2025 selection and editorial matter, S. Karthikeyan, M. Akila, D. Sumathi, and T. Poongodi. All rights reserved.
