AU  - Rzepka, S.
AU  - Hepp, M.
TI  - Reliability Testing and Virtual Prototyping for Embedded GaN Power Modules in Automotive Applications
PY  - 2024
T2  - 2024 IEEE 10th Electronics System-Integration Technology Conference, ESTC 2024 - Proceedings
DO  - 10.1109/ESTC60143.2024.10712035
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85208112646&doi=10.1109%2fESTC60143.2024.10712035&partnerID=40&md5=804014cf88cd923a16fbb2a08c41afca
AB  - The electrification of road transport requires new inverter solutions. GaN power devices offer substantial advantages in terms of electrical performance compared to Si devices and in terms of cost compared to their SiC counterparts. Embedding the semiconductor devices into organic laminates leads to very effective production technologies and robust structures with a small form factor that can be assembled with the drivetrain easily. This study focuses on the reliability of such embedded GaN power modules. During testing and operation, the module is exposed to thermal swings caused by the environment and the substantial power dissipation in the GaN device. They impose cyclic mechanical stresses within the semiconductor chips, the metallic interconnects, the organic laminates and at all interfaces between them due to the large differences in thermal expansion and stiffness of the different materials. At some critical points, the stresses can exceed the elastic range. Inelastic cyclic loading is known to cause fatigue, cracking, and failure. Therefore, reliability testing is an essential part of module development. It involves passive and active temperature cycling. The passive tests simulate the ambient conditions, e.g., the heating and cooling of the motor to which the inverter is attached, while the active power cycle test represents the operation of the module. Although the tests reasonably exaggerate the load conditions so that degradation is accelerated, they still take several weeks or even months. Virtual tests based on numerical simulations can reduce this time to a few hours. However, the virtual models and simulation results must first be calibrated and validated before they can credibly replace the physical tests. The paper covers the reliability tests, whose conditions need some adjustment to accommodate GaN devices, and presents a strategy to develop models capable of providing credible simulation results. Using the calibrated models, the measured material data has been involved to study the effect of different copper qualities on the stress level and the risk of failure. Based on this, recommendations are deduced for optimizing the module design to improve its reliability. The testing part describes the setup and presents the essential results of the passive and active thermal cycling in the form of measured data and results from the physical failure analysis. In addition, the results of dedicated material characterization are included. The simulation part describes the model creation based on a modular concept and presents the simulation results obtained in parallel to the physical passive and active temperature cycle tests based on material data from open literature. Once the tests were completed, the simulation results have been compared to the experimental findings. They agreed qualitatively but showed differences in the quantities. Adjusting the thermal boundary conditions as well as some geometric details, the simulation was repeated until the quantitative differences diminished  © 2024 IEEE.
