AB  - Perovskite with organic and lead-based cations work well, but their toxicity and stability have hindered their commercialization. In this study, we used WIEN2k software to perform first-principles calculations based on density functional theory (DFT) framework to determine the optical and electronic properties of the proposed perovskite material Rb2SnI6 to be used as an absorber for solar cells (SCs). The DFT results for band gap, carrier mobility, effective densities, and absorption spectra are put into the SCAPS (Solar Cell Capacitance Simulator)-lD software to estimate how well the proposed perovskite solar cell (PSC) structure (FTO/TiO2/Rb2SnI\epsilon/PTAA/Au) will work as a photovoltaic device. TiO2 and PTAA are employed as electron and hole transport materials respectively. We have also investigated the device performance with different organic hole transport layers (HTLs). The optimized series resistance (Rs) of 1 \Omega. cm2, Shunt resistance (Rsh) of 1 0^4\Omega. cm2, defect density of 1013cm -3, and thickness of 0.8 µm was used for the final simulation. The proposed device after optimization exhibits a Jsc of 40.4 mA/cm 2,Voc of 0. 72V, FF of 79.7 %, and PCE of 22.4 %. We also investigated the quantum efficiency (QE) of the proposed PSCs. Combination of this computational and simulation analysis of non-toxic Rb2SnI6 double perovskite (DP) reveals that it is advantageous for potential SC applications. © 2023 IEEE.
