AB  - The proceedings contain 98 papers. The special focus in this conference is on Science and Information. The topics include: Techno-Economic Assessment in Communications: New Challenges; a Low-Cost Thermal Imaging Device for Monitoring Electronic Systems Remotely; mobile Application for Bidding Durians; ADAGIO, a BDI Music Recommender Telegram Chatbot; school Bus Routing Problem-Algorithm Optimization Using Graph Theory; py-microdots: Position Encoding in the Euclidean Plane Based on the Anoto Codec; an Empirical Criterion for Transitive Closure of a Searchability Matrix; detection of Computational Propaganda on Social Networks: A Survey; quantum Computing Techniques for Multi-knapsack Problems; a Context-Aware Street Light System Based on Multi-variate Forecast and Fuzzy Logic; analysis of Syntactic Errors of Novice Python Programmers in a Nigeria University; A Constructive Heuristic “MDSA” Solving the Flexible Job Shop Scheduling Problem; j-Parallelio: Automatic Parallelization Framework for Java Virtual Machine; hyper Burst Buffer: A Lightweight Burst Buffer I/O Library for High Performance Computing Applications; electromagnetic Quantum Memory in Coherent Domains of Condensed Matter and Its Prospects for Quantum Hypercomputing; encoding Nets-Within-Nets in Maude; usage of High-Performance System in Impulsive Modelling of Hepatitis B Virus; performance Comparison of Operations in the File System and in Embedded Key-Value Databases; a Review of Usability Evaluation Methods for eHealth Applications; access Control in Mobile Crowdsensing: Requirements, Challenges and Open Issues; using Smartphone Sensing for Recognition of Game Player Attributes During Gameplay; a Game with a Purpose for Building Crowdsourced Semantic Relations Datasets for Named Entities; performing Different Clustering Methods for Mapping the European Union Member States using Green Energy, Digitalization, and R&D Indicators: A Five-Year Comparison (2016-2020); Modeling of the Modes of Operation of the AES Algorithm in the Cryptool 2 Environment; Investigating the Stability of SMOTE-Based Oversampling on COVID-19 Data.
