AB  - Through a physics-based model and a numerical simulation, it is revealed that Ge nanowires (NWs) with the 110 transport direction may deliver high intrinsic/ballistic drive currents for scaled nMOSFETs due to the optimum quantum-confined NW band structure. The quantum confinement of L-valleys in Ge 110 NW delivers both high density-of-states (DOS) due to the multiple valley degeneracy and high carrier injection velocity (inj) due to the light carrier transport mass. Comparisons of NW nMOSFETs (gate length of 13 nm) for Si, InAs, and Ge channels show that the ballistic drive currents of Ge 110 NW device are improved over Si and InAs NW devices due to the optimum combination of inj (higher than in Si) and DOS (higher than in InAs). The transport/confinement orientation is critical, e.g., Ge 100 NW does not deliver any drive current improvement over Si. © 2015 IEEE.
