AB  - The proceedings contain 34 papers. The special focus in this conference is on Methods in Scientific Computing. The topics include: Computing functionals of square root and wishart processes under the benchmark approach via exact simulation; the supremum norm of the discrepancy function; an introduction to stochastic particle integration methods; multilevel Monte Carlo methods; guaranteed conservative fixed width confidence intervals via Monte Carlo sampling; discrepancy, integration and tractability; quasi-Monte Carlo image synthesis in a nutshell; conditional sampling for barrier option pricing under the heston model; probabilistic star discrepancy bounds for double infinite random matrices; the L2 discrepancy of irrational lattices; complexity of banach space valued and parametric integration; extended Latin hypercube sampling for integration and simulation; a kernel-based collocation method for elliptic partial differential equations with random coefficients; polynomial accelerated MCMC and other sampling algorithms inspired by computational optimization; antithetic multilevel Monte Carlo estimation for multidimensional SDEs; on the convergence of quantum and sequential Monte Carlo methods; lower error bounds for randomized multilevel and changing dimension algorithms; a non-empirical test on the second to the sixth least significant bits of pseudorandom number generators; a finite-row scrambling of niederreiter sequences; reconstructing multivariate trigonometric polynomials by sampling along generated sets; Bayesian approaches to the design of Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers; deterministic consistent density estimation for light transport simulation; on wavelet-galerkin methods for semilinear parabolic equations with additive noise; component-by-component construction of hybrid point sets based on hammersley and lattice point sets; a QMC-spectral method for elliptic PDEs with random coefficients on the unit sphere; sampling and low-rank tensor approxima