AB  - An area X-ray digital detector operating at relatively high photon energies (140 kVp) is modeled and its performance evaluated using Monte Carlo techniques. The simulated model allowed us also to show up (through synthetic images) how the sequences of physical processes, i.e. signal propagation through the overall imaging system and detector chain, influence the performance of the detector. The modeling of the detector includes the spatial distribution of absorbed X-rays statistics, its conversion into light and transmission, and finally light quanta conversion into electrons. The light transport within the fibers and its influence is examined and taken into account in a zero and non-zero frequency analysis. It is also included the contributions to the noise from the detection system chain, mainly the CCDs sensor "ambient" noise. As a result, our modeling procedure permitted us to evaluate the detector performance characteristics. Especially DQE, MTF and SNR with estimated values ∼70% (8-140 keV), ∼20 lp mm-1 and 3.0, respectively. The modeling procedure of the imaging system proved to be an excellent tool for imaging system parameters and components optimization and may also be suitable for overall computed tomography (CT) and digital radiography (RD) system performance prediction. © 2003 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.
