TI  - Fabrication and performance of high speed InGaAs APDs
PY  - 1990
T2  - Technical Digest Series
SP  - 148
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-0025629426&partnerID=40&md5=dd49dc51ae5bde43e0e591cd42eefaf3
AB  - The optimization, fabrication, and performance of a separated absorption and multiplication (SAM) avalanche photodiode (APD) are discussed. To obtain high reliability, the device has a planar design and employs a double guard ring formed by ion implantation into an InGaAs heterostructure grown by trichloride vapor-phase epitaxy (VPE). Computer simulation was employed to optimize the guard ring design to give a high degree of gain uniformity and subnanoampere dark current for low-noise operation. A tradeoff between dark current and response speed requires careful control of the electric field at the InGaAsP-InP heterointerface. The control is achieved by careful placement of the different center junction. An InGaAsP grading layer eases the constraint, but the junction must still be placed with an accuracy of ±200 angstrom to achieve optimum performance. The design of the absorption layer thickness requires a tradeoff between quantum efficiency and transit time. The constraint is eased by use of a reflecting contact to allow a thin absorbing region for high speed while retaining a high quantum efficiency. A thin multiplication layer and careful control of the electric field profile lead to gain-bandwidth products as high as 86 GHz and bandwidths as high as 7 GHz at M = 10.
